<Base title="Reproduce, Don't Assess — Augmented Engineering">
  <PatternPage number="4" title="Reproduce, Don't Assess" subtitle="When checking equations, compute the answer. Don't ask if it looks right." advisory={true}>

    <p>There are two ways to verify numerical content with an AI:</p>

    <p><strong>Assessment:</strong> "Review these equations for correctness." The agent checks dimensions, evaluates plausibility, assesses consistency. This is what human reviewers do — and what LLMs default to.</p>

    <p><strong>Reproduction:</strong> "Substitute these values, compute step-by-step, and compare your result to the stated answer." The agent becomes a calculator, not a reviewer.</p>

    <p>The difference matters enormously.</p>

    <div class="illustration-wrap">
      <IllustrationReproduce />
    </div>

    <h2>The Prompt Pattern</h2>

    <pre><code>For each equation:
1. EXTRACT: Write the equation; list all inputs with values
2. DIMENSIONAL ANALYSIS: Verify units balance
3. NUMERICAL REPRODUCTION: Substitute values, compute step-by-step
4. CONSISTENCY CHECK: Does this value appear elsewhere?
5. CROSS-REFERENCE: Does it match the source?

RULES:
- Never skip a calculation. Show all work.
- Trust nothing. Treat every number as potentially wrong.
- When checking tables: verify EVERY row.</code></pre>

    <div class="monday-box">
      <h3>Try This Monday</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Next time you need to verify a calculation or derived value: don't ask "is this right?" Ask "compute this from scratch and compare."</li>
        <li>Use the prompt pattern above. The key instruction: "show all work, skip nothing."</li>
        <li>Use assessment mode for <em>conceptual</em> review (wrong model? missing physics?) and reproduction mode for <em>numerical</em> verification. They catch different things.</li>
        <li>Beware "remaining rows follow the same pattern..." — if the model summarizes instead of computing, errors slip through.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Where This Comes From</h2>

    <p>68 equations governing electromagnetic pendulum synchronization. Three independent reviews:</p>

    <div class="evidence-box">
      <p><strong>Claude assessment:</strong> "physics soundness" check &rarr; <strong>0 errors found</strong></p>
      <p><strong>Gemini assessment:</strong> "physics soundness" check &rarr; <strong>0 errors found</strong></p>
      <p><strong>Sonnet reproduction:</strong> substitute values, compute step-by-step &rarr; <strong>3 errors found</strong></p>
    </div>

    <p>The three errors:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Wrong label.</strong> A table headed "5 degrees" contained values computed at 1 degree. 5x error. The table <em>looked</em> right.</li>
      <li><strong>Formula error.</strong> Dwell time: predicted 84ms, table said 43ms. Plausible formula, wrong coefficients.</li>
      <li><strong>Inconsistency.</strong> 3.3 ms/swing &times; 3600 swings/hr = ~12 s/hr. Document stated 36 s/hr. Each number individually plausible.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>All three: correct units, reasonable magnitude, coherent with surrounding text. Invisible to assessment. Immediately visible to arithmetic.</p>

    <div class="caveat-box">
      <h3>Honest Limitations</h3>
      <p>The 3/3 detection rate is from one document. The comparison (Gemini: 0, Sonnet: 3) is confounded by different model AND different prompt. Reasoning-augmented models are improving at mathematical judgment — this specific technique may become unnecessary within 18 months. The principle "independently verify, don't just review" is permanent.</p>
    </div>

  </PatternPage>
</Base>
